### What is  Cardinality??
cardinality defines the nature of the relationship between two tables by specifying how many rows in one table relate to rows in another
Common Cardinality Types:
One-to-Many (1:*): One record in Table A relates to multiple records in Table B (e.g., one Customer to many Orders).
Many-to-One (*:1): The reverse of 1:*, where multiple rows in Table A link to a single row in Table B (e.g., many Orders to one Customer).
One-to-One (1:1): Each record in Table A has exactly one related record in Table B, and vice versa (e.g., splitting a large table).
Many-to-Many (*:*): Rows in both tables can have multiple related rows (e.g., Products and Tags). 
Used for Filtering, to ensure correct connections

